node.text:
Why #wildlife is my favorite travel experience: 
1) You need some luck to see it
2) effort & patience needed
3) they often live more remote
4) every picture is unique
5) I like cats üò∫

#puma #fox #guacano #caracara #torresdelpaine #patagonia #patagoniawildlife #patagoniatravel #wanderluster #chile

Nice hike up to the famous Torres peaks. Torres del Paine has beautifull trails and views on the W track. However if you wish to hike this 5 day track, better prepare in advance! Spots are limited and often fully booked months ahead.

#torresdelpaine #chilehiking #naturegram #view #torres #patagonia #patogoniatravel #wanderluster #digitalnomad #cryptonomad

The #Guanaco is the secret to spotting puma's. They live in packs and usually have a "spotter" on higher grounds and have a distinctive sound to alarm each other if the see any danger üîä
-
If you hear their alarm and see several spotters, preferably on different hills, and see them looking in the same direction. There is a good properbility of a puma presence. Watch their behavior to find the puma's!

#wildlife #naturegram #torresdelpaine #torresdelpainewildlife #patagonia #patogoniatravel #patagoniawildlife #wanderluster #chile

Purr-fect! What a day! We knew the #Puma population is Torres del Paine in quite healthy, but it seemed impossible to find them during our hikes.
-
We decided to look for help, and found wildlife photographer Miguel @iso100outdoor who was willing to take us on a day of Puma tracking, starting at 4am üïì
-
Before we reached the national park entry, Miguel & Pau @pauamurgo already spotted a pack of 4 Puma's at a far distance. We decided to stay on the road, and follow them to see if they would move closer to us. After 4 hours, Miguel noticed they are moving towards a lake. So we parked our car on a spot where they would likely cross the road. üí•Jackpot!
-
Many thanks to Miguel & Pau, who provided an awesome day with a great #wildlifeexperience
-
#patagoniawildlife #patagonia #patogoniatravel #torresdelpaine #torresdelpainewildlife #wildlifephotography #mountainlion #cougar  #wildcat #catsofinstagram #wanderluster

The Kalahari bushmen are one of the few true hunter-gatherer "nomad" cultures still on this planet.

While we were enjoying home made sangria at night around a campfire with dancing tribe men, Yas said she felt ill. While we walked to our tents she fainted! Luckily our group we traveled with all jumped to help. As I carried Yas on my shoulders, she came to unaware what happened.

Before diner Yas went for a run, in the desert. She didn't think to hydrate, which caused the short pass out.

A small scare, in a unique scenario. It will be a memory I will smile at my whole life

The most asked question since we are back is "what was you favorite place?" I don't have a favorite place, but I do have favorite experiences. I will share a couple over the next weeks.

I have read about "devils pool" in Zambia a few years back. Since I found out about it I was waiting for the oppertunity to head out there. When planning our Africa tour I made sure we would make it to Victoria falls.

Once we were there I had to convince Yas to join me. It didn't help that we visited the Zimbabwe side first, so Yas could see the brute forces of nature before swimming in it.... It feels weird laying on the edge of the biggest waterfalls of Africa, hearing the water crush against the rocks, while there is only 1 rope for security. That is tied to a small handing tree.

The most scary thing about this whole experience was the guide that took our pictures. He was jumping around snapping shots while he was a few inches away from certain death.

When you are on the road, don't say no to unique experiences ‚úåÔ∏è #victoriafalls #zimbabwe #Zambia #digitalnomad #travelcouple #devilspool #angelsarmchair #worldnomads #tia #thisisafrica #worldtrip #worldtraveler #couples #trybeforeyoudie

Day 220 - Phayao - Thailand, I first came to Thailand in 2013. I visited the most common touristy places and was not a big fan of it all. I was backpacking through South - East Asia and of the whole trip Thailand was my least favorite one. Looking back I am not exactly sure what it was. A travel experience is influenced by many factors. The people you meet, the places you stay, the weather, the restaurants you eat at and a random factor. I just didn't get the right mix at my first visit.

This is my 3rd "block" of staying in Chiang Mai for a few months since 2013. Accumulated I stayed over a year in Thailand. It is now my favorite country in Asia to stay at. I have lots of friends and it actually feels like home in Chiang Mai. Don't let a bad holiday ruin your impression of a country for the rest of your life. Give it Atleast another try and hope you get the right mix of factors to make it a good experience ‚úåÔ∏è

7/7 of the wonders of the world! Machu Picchu truely lives up to the hype. One of my favorite trips of all time was going to Chile , Peru and Bolovia in 2014
***Storytime***
We did a 4 day tour to get to Machu Picchu. In those days you get to hike the Andes and you have some fun activities on the way like ziplining or mountainbikingüöµ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è. In those 4 days you get to walk a lot of Kilometers. If you have a hike experience you must know awesome the feeling of getting to the top or your destination. You feel happy, tired, hungry, satisfied and a whole spectrum of emotions. The one that always stands out for me is happiness. Imagine hiking in the heat for 4 days to arrive at Machu Picchu the hiden Inca city! 
The morning we got to Machu Picchu we raced up the 1000 stone stairs in the dark at 5am to get to the gates first. When we got there we had all the time to take pictures witout other tourist and fine a nice spot to enjoy the  sunrise. Arguably the best sunrise of my/our  life!

In 2014 I did a trip in central America with a good friend from high school. He is the type of person who doesn't have any social media account and does not like selfie'sü§≥. So I ended up with a picture of myself here at Chichen Itza, the 6th wonder of the world for me.

Chichen Itza is a very impressive archaeological site. Its one of the biggest Mayan cities ever discovered and you can feel the history when you walk around there. Right before i visited Chichen Itza I saw the movie Apacolypto directed by Mel Gibson. The first of the 7 wonders that I visited was back in 2012. When i visited the Corcovada in Rio de Janeiro I got super exited. The view from there over the city was amazing. I decided I had to visit all 7 of them, which took me about 3 years to complete. ***storytime***
I spend 3 months in Brazil in 2012. I spoke 0 Spanish or Portugese at that time. I was a novice traveler. I remember I was amazed by this sight, but in retrospect it was the least impressive wonder. Don't get me wrong, it is a beatiful place to visit. But all the other wonders raise archaeological questions, have culture history, had societies live there and took years to build. The corcovado is a huge religious statue on a small mountain with a great view.
Travelling is not only seeing beutiful places. It's a learning proces of the worlds history through talking to people and visiting historical sights. That is something I missed here. That being said, defelinitly check it out if your get the chance!

Petra was the last of the 7 wonders we visited in 2015. The combination of brutal heat & ancient history is something all travelers should experience.
***storytime***
I was eager to go here l, so i could tick this big thing of my #bucketlist. To see all 7 wonders of the world was something I aspired for a few years. When we finally arrived at the gates we knew we had some walking to do before we get to Petra. Once Yas saw everyone was wearing hikingboots, while she was on flipflops I saw in her eyes she had a small panic attack. "OMG look at all the boots", she said quite loud. I told just put one foot infront of the other and we keep walking untill we get to the end. Almost like a life lesson. Luckily it was not as far as we feared and we had an awesome time exploring this historical site. Petra deserves to be on everybody's bucketlist. We feel its the most underestimated sight of the 7 wonder of the world.üèõüåé

The great wall of China is an impressive sight. I thought this is the only thing mankind build that you could see from space, or atleast the lower earth orbit. However when I do some research I find out this is an urban myth. Still this is one of my favorite sites of the 7 wonders of the world.
***storytime***
This was my final stop of backpacking 3 months through Asia in 2013. I thought i was experienced enough to find my way to the great wall, I mean how hard can that be right? I had a very difficult time at the trainstation explaining where I wanted to go, so desperatly I was looking around the trainstation for people who looked like they would understand English. I found two Russian girls who happened to be heading to the great wall aswell and they were kind enough to let me tag along ü§ó Because of them I had the chance to experience this world wonder. I tried to find a picture with the 3 of us at the wall, but sadly i Lost them.  We had such a good time I even visited them in St. Petersburg a year later! @lerryleryy and @voplstudio thanks for the awesome experiences, and if you still have some pics please email themü§£

Day 107, Thailand, This picture is from my first visit to Thailand in 2013. It was my first solo backpacking experience of a few months trough Asia. In 2016 my friends convinced me to stay with them in Chiang Mai for 3 months. I was trying to convince them to pick another country, but they were hard headed and I couldn't negotiate about a different location. I was forced to give Thailand another try. The 3 months in CM totally changed my perspective on Thailand. I ‚ù§Ô∏è this country so much now, and I was very excited to come back here with Yas for some weeks/months. Day 103, Picture taken in Etosha - Namibia, Our trip this year started with a Nomad tour from Capetown to Victoria Falls and ended in Kruger National Park. We traveled 8200 km over land in 26 days and visited 5 countries in that time. We couldn't have wished for a better way to start our world tour! We met amazing people, made friends, had the best crew and we saw and experienced a ton of new things. The excitement we felt when we saw the first lions has not been matched yet. ü¶Å
**story behind this pic**
After a full day of game drive in Etosha National Park we were on our way to the camp siteüèïÔ∏è. Everyone was tired of the long drives, staring our the window trying to spot wildlife will make you very sleepy! We saw a lot of wildlife and I practiced a ton with my new Cameraüì∑. We were very happy with the animals we got to see. Then suddenly our driver puts the break pedal to the floor. Everyone was shocked, why did the driver make a sudden stop?? We looked at the window and two lions walked right passed our truck. They were almost close enough to touch! One big male and one younger male just casually walked by, they looked back once and continued their journey. Perfect day for us! ü¶Åü¶Å if you are planning to go to Africa  check out Nomad tours! -

How was everyone's Easter?! This pic of Easter Island is from my trip in 2014. I have never topped the excitement I felt when I took my first steps out the the airplane to set foot on this island. It was on my bucketlist for years and I was exited and curious to explore the island. Why is it called Easter Island? A Dutch (yes always the dutch) sailor discovered this island when it was Easter. So instead of naming the island Roggeveen (his name), it was named Easter Island. Today it's part of Chille and the most remote island in the world. Easter will always remind me of my visit to #easterisland

Our Africa part of the world tour is over!  Heading to Qatar for a few days while we are on our way to Nepal. 
People often ask me how I get to travel the world or how I get to hold this lifestyle.  I have a simple 5 step strategy  1) set a goal 2) make a plan how to achieve this goal 3) execute the plan 4) achieve the goal 5) repeat 
It might sound simple but without setting #goals and making a plan you are just dreaming. Maybe I come of like an ass hole by stating it is as simple as this,  but people overcomplicate things. 
One of my personal highlights of the start of our trip is this swim in the Angels Armchair at Victoria Falls at the Zambia side. Not strapped or hooked in anywhere,  just a small robe and 1 guide (who also has no security)  to keep you from sliding off the rocks into infinity.  I found out about this pool years ago and I put it on my #bucketlist It's the reason we decided to travel from Capetown all the way to Victoria Falls on this trip. We traveled 8200km on dusty roads to get to this spot and it was worth it! Goodbye #Africa,  see you next time.

Last days In Africa for the year.  In 5.5 weeks we traveled through 5 countries in southern Africa.  Amazing experience because of the people we met,  scenery and wildlife.  Everything about this trip was awesome and I just sing the Lego song all day "everything is awesome when you're part of a team!" Just chill mode last days in Capetown  #muizenberg #pokernomad

A non safari day in Africa.  Doing the panoramic route in the Kruger area.  This is Blyde river Canyon,  the 3rd  biggest Canyon in the world.  It wasn't on our bucket list but by coincidence we will see the 3 biggest canyons in the world on our year trip ^^

#3 out of the big 5! We got very close on our boat on Chobe River to get this spectacular view of the Buffalo.  Chobe is a beautiful national park with amazing scenery and very divers wildlife. 
Also got to spot my first wild dog!  Only 6600 wild dogs live on this planet and we are lucky enough to have seen one! 
On our way to Kruger National Park  now.  We will camp in Kruger for 3 nights and hope to complete the big 5. Still need the rhino and leopard.  But even if we dont see them,  we are very satisfied with what we got to see up till now ^^ #buffalo #chobe #bigfive #big5

The bushman of Kalahari Desert,  original hunters &  gatherers.  All homo sapiens used to live like them before agriculture Revolution,  it's mind blowing how they survive and the knowledge the have. #therealnomads #namibia

Literally living on the edge! Devils pool was closed due to rainy season,  angels pool is just as amazing!  Feel the power of nature,  get the adrenaline pumping. Proud @crossfityas she had the "balls"  to do this üòçüòé #victoriafalls #angelspool #devilspool

Arrived in Zimbabwe.  Tomorrow we are going to swim in these waterfalls.  Devils pool is closed due to rainy season  but angels armchair at the Zambia side is open for the daredevils who want to swim in Africa's biggest waterfalls #trybeforeyoudie

Spend some rainy days In Botswana delta trying to spot Hippos,  we mostly saw crocks but today in Namibia we saw 7 Hippos already so it's all good! üòÅüòÜ Cruising around in these mokoro boats in the delta was an unique experience! #delta #botswana
On our drive out ethosa National Park we spotted 3 elephant's and more lions :) lucky drive out for us! Heading back to civilization now,  next stop Windhoek the capital of #namibia
